The paper discusses the use of data mining techniques to identify useful macro-actions for state space planning, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The proposed algorithm also involves machine learning techniques, which are commonly used in the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also mentions the integration of learned macro-actions in planning search, which is related to the sub-category of robotics (cs.RO). Additionally, the paper focuses on planning benchmarks, which is a key area of research in the sub-category of planning and scheduling (cs.PL). Finally, the paper discusses the use of macro-actions to improve planning performance, which is relevant to the sub-category of control systems (cs.SY).
